The large macroeconomic divergence
PARIS – „The global expansion has reached its peak,” warns the OECD in its latest economic outlook, and performance could suffer if downside risks materialize.
The party is not over yet: it is expected that global growth will continue in the years 2019 and 2020 – albeit at a slower pace.
However, economic forecasters are notoriously bad at identifying macroeconomic turning points, and the future economic course is difficult to assess.
Potential obstacles abound: the more aggressive monetary tightening, especially in the United States; a further escalation of protectionism; an economic landing in China that proves to be harsher than expected; and a return of tensions in the Eurozone, triggered by concerns regarding the fate of Italian public finances.
All these or even each of these developments could exacerbate the downturn that has already begun.
A recession in the USA would be frustrating for President Donald Trump, who is already eyeing his 2020 re-election, although such a development would not contradict known patterns.
Officially, the expansion began in June 2009, and with a duration until July 2019, it would be the longest such phase in the economic history of the USA.
Unemployment is at its lowest level since the 1960s.
Under these conditions, the implementation of the economic policies of the Trump administration, consisting of massive tax cuts and increased spending – that is, a stimulus package comparable to that of 2009, which was intended to prevent an impending depression – is economically not sensible.
Damit bleiben der Notenbank Federal Reserve nur zwei Möglichkeiten: entweder sie hebt die Zinssätze drastischer an, um die zeitlich schlecht geplanten Konjunkturmaßnahmen auszugleichen oder sie kapituliert.
Ein derart verantwortungsloses Feiglingsspiel zwischen den amerikanischen Haushalts- und Währungsbehörden lässt angesichts der weltweiten Auswirkungen des US-Zinszyklus das Risiko der Instabilität auch im Rest der Welt ansteigen.
Eine globale Rezession käme für jene Länder mehr als zu früh, deren Erholung verzögert einsetzte oder schwach ausfiel oder beides.
Ein Extrembeispiel ist Griechenland, wo das Wachstum erst 2017 anzog und die Arbeitslosigkeit immer noch fast 20 Prozent beträgt.
Aber Griechenland ist nicht allein.
In Italy, per capita GDP is not higher than in the mid-1990s.
And in Spain, France, South Korea, and other countries, unemployment is still significantly above pre-crisis levels.
The challenge is to bring long-term unemployed individuals, for whom the risk of skill degradation exists, back into employment.
To prevent a lasting socio-economic damage, these countries need faster growth.
A promising international situation alone cannot solve their problems, but would help maximize the benefits of national reforms.
The other extreme is the German labor market, which is currently in much better shape than in 2007.
In the western federal states, full employment prevails and economic growth is increasingly dependent on immigration: in 2017, the net inflow – not refugees, but migrants from other European countries – amounted to nearly 400,000 people.
In Japan, the United Kingdom, and Poland, the recovery was also characterized by the creation of many jobs.
Citizens complain about income, inequality, or rising house prices, but not about a lack of jobs.
Ten years ago, the crisis hit almost all developed economies simultaneously.
Today, they do not present themselves either structurally or cyclically on a single line.
This is indeed alarming, as the cooling down of the global economy is occurring at a time of increasing political fragility.
Trust in governments and institutions of political decision-making is – understandably – extremely low.
Collective economic mismanagement would only further erode this trust and fuel the already rising economic nationalism.
What is to be done now?
The list of tasks to be tackled begins at home. In many countries, where the labor market is still out of balance, national measures are needed to strengthen the economic potential and improve access to jobs.
In France, employers report a skills shortage despite an unemployment rate of 9 percent and reforms by President Emmanuel Macron.
To change this, comprehensive measures in the education sector are just as necessary as support for mobility, incentives for job acceptance, and the opening of protected sectors.
This is already happening.
In Italy, however, the ruling coalition has initiated an economic stimulus program and at the same time proposed measures to reduce labor participation.
Dazu zählen etwa die Rücknahme der Rentenreform des Jahres 2011 sowie die Einführung eines „Bürgereinkommens“, das im Falle unzureichender Planung oder Umsetzung dazu führen wird, dass weniger Menschen einer Beschäftigung nachgehen.
Diese politische Widersprüchlichkeit und weniger Italiens Abweichung von den Haushaltsregeln der Europäischen Union ist der wahre Grund zur Besorgnis.
Die zweite Priorität besteht darin, ein Risikogleichgewicht herzustellen.
Seit geraumer Zeit entspinnt sich eine politische Debatte zwischen politischen Falken und Tauben, wobei erstere davor warnen, dass die Aufkäufe von Vermögenswerten durch die Zentralbanken sowie die nahe Null liegenden Zinssätze finanzielle Instabilität und Inflationsrisiken schüren. Die größte Sorge der Tauben hingegen gilt der Deflation.
Beides ist durchaus real, wobei allerdings mehr Grund für die Sorge vor Deflation besteht.
Real estate price bubbles can be tempered through regulatory measures, such as capping the ratio of loan amount to the property's value or between loan amount and income.
With regard to inflation, forecasts are regularly proven wrong.
Wages have so far slowly responded to the declining unemployment rate.
There is a well-founded fear of a possible abrupt increase, but after so many years of under-inflation, one can reasonably take on this risk.
The collective costs of a temporary inflation overshoot fade in comparison to those of an early recession, which leads to lasting damages and a political backlash against economic orthodoxy.
The third priority, international coordination, is by far the most difficult to achieve, especially in the Eurozone, where the European Central Bank pursues a unified policy for different national economies.
The standard solution would involve the ECB targeting the average inflation rate and relying on national fiscal policy to fine-tune the macroeconomic course.
However, due to higher debt or remaining deficits, the countries that would need further growth are precisely those that have no fiscal policy room for maneuver.
Neither Greece nor Italy, nor even Spain or France, can currently consider a substantial stimulus program.
Without the possibility of cross-country transfers (which are also not provided for in the recent agreement between France and Germany on a mini-Eurozone budget), this is another reason why the ECB should act more boldly.
This would leave the governments of countries threatened by overheating with the task of cooling down their economies using fiscal policy tools, while the governments of countries still struggling to improve their economies would be tasked with unlocking their economic potential.
There are numerous reasons to doubt that this is possible.
It is the task of political decision-makers to manage risks, even though the risks of today are not the usual ones.
The resilience of the global economic system is at stake.
Despite favorable conditions, initial cracks are showing.
It must be prevented that this leads to fractures.
